const faqSchema = { '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'FAQPage', mainEntity: [
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How does sea moss support thyroid health?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Sea moss (Chondrus crispus) is a red algae naturally rich in iodine — the essential mineral required for thyroid hormone synthesis. A single serving of sea moss can contain 47-157mcg of iodine depending on harvest location, species, and preparation. The thyroid gland requires iodine to produce T3 and T4 hormones, which regulate metabolism, energy, body temperature, and cognitive function. Sea moss also contains selenium, zinc, and other trace minerals that support thyroid enzyme function. However, iodine content in sea moss varies significantly, making standardized supplementation important for those specifically targeting thyroid support.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How much sea moss should I take for thyroid support?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Most sea moss gummies provide 500mg-3,000mg of sea moss extract per serving, with iodine content varying from 30-200mcg depending on the source. For thyroid support, the key metric is iodine delivery — the RDA for iodine is 150mcg for adults. Since sea moss iodine content is variable, look for products that standardize or test for iodine content rather than just listing the raw sea moss amount. Taking 1-2 gummies daily (as directed on the label) is typically sufficient. Do not take excessive amounts, as too much iodine can worsen thyroid conditions including Hashimoto thyroiditis and Graves disease.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is the benefit of bladderwrack in sea moss gummies?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Bladderwrack (Fucus vesiculosus) is a brown seaweed that has been used in traditional medicine for thyroid support for centuries. It is one of the richest natural sources of iodine and also contains fucoidans — sulfated polysaccharides with documented anti-inflammatory, antioxidant, and immune-modulating properties. When combined with sea moss, bladderwrack provides additional iodine and complementary bioactive compounds. A 2014 review in Marine Drugs confirmed fucoidan\'s antioxidant and anti-inflammatory effects. The sea moss + bladderwrack combination is the most popular thyroid-targeted formulation in the natural supplement market.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Is sea moss safe for people with Hashimoto thyroiditis?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Sea moss should be used with extreme caution — or avoided entirely — by individuals with Hashimoto thyroiditis without explicit guidance from an endocrinologist. Hashimoto is an autoimmune condition where the immune system attacks the thyroid gland. Excess iodine intake can trigger or worsen thyroid inflammation (thyroiditis) and increase thyroid antibody levels in Hashimoto patients. While some individuals with Hashimoto may be iodine-deficient and could benefit from controlled supplementation, self-medicating with variable-iodine sea moss products is not recommended. Always get thyroid antibody levels and TSH tested before starting any iodine-containing supplement.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What other minerals does sea moss contain besides iodine?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Sea moss is often marketed as containing 92 of the 102 minerals the body needs. While this claim is not scientifically verified, sea moss does contain a broad mineral profile including iodine, selenium (essential for T4-to-T3 conversion), zinc (supports thyroid hormone receptor binding), iron, magnesium, calcium, potassium, phosphorus, and manganese. It also contains sulfated polysaccharides, amino acids, and vitamins A, C, E, and K. The mineral content varies significantly by species, harvest location, water temperature, and processing method.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Can I take sea moss gummies while on thyroid medication?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'You should consult your endocrinologist before combining sea moss with thyroid medication (levothyroxine, liothyronine, or natural desiccated thyroid). Sea moss provides iodine, which can affect thyroid hormone production and potentially alter your medication requirements. Taking sea moss may increase iodine intake enough to change TSH levels, requiring medication dose adjustments. Additionally, some sea moss supplements contain minerals (calcium, iron, magnesium) that can interfere with levothyroxine absorption if taken at the same time. If your doctor approves sea moss, take it at least 4 hours apart from thyroid medication.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is the difference between sea moss and kelp for thyroid?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Sea moss (Chondrus crispus) is a red algae, while kelp (Laminaria, Ascophyllum, and others) is a brown algae. Both contain iodine, but kelp typically has higher iodine concentrations — potentially 10-100x more than sea moss per gram. This makes kelp more potent but also more risky for iodine overdose. Sea moss is generally considered a gentler iodine source with a broader mineral profile and additional bioactive compounds (carrageenan, sulfated polysaccharides). For thyroid support, kelp provides more concentrated iodine, while sea moss provides a more moderate, whole-food approach with additional nutritional benefits.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How long does it take for sea moss to affect the thyroid?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'If thyroid function is limited by iodine deficiency, replenishing iodine stores can improve thyroid hormone levels within 2-4 weeks. TSH (thyroid-stimulating hormone) typically begins to normalize within this timeframe. However, sea moss is not a treatment for thyroid disease — it simply provides iodine and trace minerals that support normal thyroid function. If your thyroid dysfunction is caused by autoimmune disease (Hashimoto or Graves), structural abnormalities, or other non-nutritional factors, sea moss alone will not resolve the underlying condition. Always work with an endocrinologist for thyroid concerns.' } },
] };
