    <div class="ing-box"><h4>Sea Moss for Thyroid: What the Science Says</h4><p>Sea moss provides iodine and trace minerals essential for thyroid function, though clinical research specific to sea moss supplements is still emerging.</p><div class="vs-strip">
      <div class="vs-item"><strong>Iodine and Thyroid Hormones</strong><p>Iodine is structurally incorporated into T3 and T4. Without it, thyroid hormone production ceases. Sea moss provides 47-157mcg per serving.<br /><em>Endocrine Reviews, 2009</em></p></div>
      <div class="vs-item"><strong>Bladderwrack Fucoidans</strong><p>Fucoidans from bladderwrack demonstrate anti-inflammatory and immune-modulating properties that may benefit thyroid autoimmune conditions.<br /><em>Marine Drugs, 2014</em></p></div>
      <div class="vs-item"><strong>Selenium for T4-to-T3</strong><p>Selenium activates deiodinase enzymes and improved thyroid antibody levels in Hashimoto patients across multiple trials.<br /><em>Thyroid, 2017</em></p></div>
      <div class="vs-item"><strong>Iodine Variability Concern</strong><p>Commercial sea moss products showed iodine content varying from 16-385mcg per serving, highlighting the need for standardized products.<br /><em>Food Chemistry, 2021</em></p></div>
    </div></div>

