    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Sea Moss Gummies for Thyroid</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How does sea moss support thyroid health?</summary><p>Sea moss is rich in iodine — the essential mineral for thyroid hormone synthesis. It also contains selenium, zinc, and other trace minerals that support the complete thyroid hormone lifecycle.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much sea moss should I take for thyroid support?</summary><p>Most products provide 500-1,500mg per serving. The key metric is iodine delivery (150mcg RDA). Look for products that standardize iodine content rather than just listing raw sea moss weight.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the benefit of bladderwrack?</summary><p>Bladderwrack adds iodine and contains fucoidans with anti-inflammatory properties. It is the traditional companion to sea moss in thyroid support formulations.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Is sea moss safe for Hashimoto thyroiditis?</summary><p>Use extreme caution. Excess iodine can worsen Hashimoto. Do not take sea moss without endocrinologist approval and thyroid antibody monitoring.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What other minerals does sea moss contain?</summary><p>Selenium, zinc, iron, magnesium, calcium, potassium, phosphorus, and manganese, plus vitamins A, C, E, and K. Content varies by species and origin.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take sea moss while on thyroid medication?</summary><p>Consult your endocrinologist. Sea moss iodine can alter thyroid function and medication requirements. Take at least 4 hours apart from levothyroxine.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the difference between sea moss and kelp?</summary><p>Kelp has 10-100x more iodine per gram than sea moss. Sea moss provides gentler iodine with a broader mineral profile. Sea moss is the safer choice for daily supplementation.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long does it take for sea moss to affect the thyroid?</summary><p>If thyroid function is limited by iodine deficiency, TSH can begin normalizing within 2-4 weeks. Sea moss is not a treatment for thyroid disease — consult an endocrinologist.</p></details>

    <div class="warn-box"><span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span><p><strong>Critical:</strong> Sea moss and bladderwrack contain significant iodine. Individuals with thyroid conditions (Hashimoto, Graves, nodules), those taking thyroid medication, and pregnant women should consult an endocrinologist before use. Excessive iodine can worsen thyroid autoimmunity and cause both hypo- and hyperthyroidism.</p></div>

